I‚Äôve known about this place for some time and only recently got round to taking some photos before going to the archery range next door and wish I‚Äôd
visited earlier! The bay itself is worth a visit if you‚Äôre in the area as there‚Äôs the main lookout with a couple of wrecks however it‚Äôs the ‚Äúfloating forest‚Äù which is the highlight, with healthy green trees growing out of the 100+ year old

Especially because you won‚Äôt be the first person to get this aerial shot so they may not welcome another drone hovering outside their window.

Petit coin au coeur de Sydney rempli de points d'int√©r√™t. Une installation artistique que beaucoup de gens ignorent est ¬´ Distance of Your Heart ¬ª. Ce sont 60 oiseaux en bronze perch√©s le long de Bridge Street. C'est toute une aventure de les retrouver ! 12 se trouvent dans le parc, ainsi que le banc portant le nom de l'installation.

Vous trouverez √©galement l'ob√©lisque de Macquarie, le point de mesure original de Sydney (notez que les mesures sont en miles¬†!).

Et un canon et une ancre du Sirius, vaisseau amiral de la Premi√®re Flotte.

Il y a un puits original "garde le trottoir au sec !" et si vous regardez le coin NE, vous verrez un d√¥me de fer. Il s'agissait autrefois de toilettes publiques, mais elles ont √©t√© combl√©es depuis longtemps.

En tant que parc, c'est un peu minable, mais si vous souhaitez vous asseoir, marchez simplement un p√¢t√© de maisons jusqu'√† Circular Quay pour une vue imprenable. Et il y a une magnifique petite ruelle du c√¥t√© nord pour prendre un verre.

originalText.text:
Little spot in the heart of Sydney packed with points of interest. One that many people don't know about is the 'Distance of Your Heart' art installation. It's 60 bronze birds perched along Bridge Street. It's quite an adventure to find them! 12 are in the park, as well as the bench with the name of the installation.

You'll also find Macquarie's obelisk, the original measuring point for Sydney (notice the measurements are in miles!).

And a cannon and anchor from the Sirius, flagship of the First Fleet.

There's an original well "keep the pavement dry!" and if you look at the NE corner, you'll see an iron dome. These used to be public toilets, but were long ago filled in.

As a park, it's a bit grotty, but if you're looking to sit, just walk a block to Circular Quay for amazing views. And there's a gorgeous little laneway on the northern side for drinks.

Profitez des nombreuses reliques historiques, de l'√©tat de Thomas Sutcliffe Mort [et non de Lachlan Macquarie], d'une sculpture d'oiseau, de l'ancre du Sirius et de son canon, des toilettes publiques souterraines restantes [disparues depuis longtemps] et de quelques autres ornements.

Fait amusant, c'√©tait le premier espace public officiellement publi√© en Australie apr√®s la colonisation europ√©enne de l'Australie, bien qu'il soit beaucoup plus petit aujourd'hui qu'il ne l'√©tait lorsqu'il √©tait la seule place publique d'Australie.

originalText.text:
A very pretty, scenic quiet spot tucked away from a lot of hustle and bustle on weekends. Enjoy the many historic relics, a state of Thomas Sutcliffe Mort [not Lachlan Macquarie], a bird sculpture, the anchor of the Sirius and its cannon, remannt underground public toilets [long gone] and a few other ornaments.

Fun fact, it was the first officially gazetted public space in Australia post European Colonisation of Australia, although it's much smaller today than it was when it was Australia's only public square.

Floating Forest of Homebush Bay, Sydney, Australia

Contrary to its name, the Floating Forest is not, in fact, a forest. It‚Äôs a decommissioned ship sitting in Homebush Bay, and its name refers to the greenery that has overtaken the hull. Fully grown mangrove trees now adorn this rusted old boat, lending some color and life to an abandoned vessel. Originally called the SS Ayrfield, the boat was built in 1911 in the UK as a steam collier, and was later used to bring supplies to US troops stationed in the Pacific during World War II. It was retired in 1972 and sent to Homebush Bay, where it has remained ever since.
